@helixbass what do you think of this minor refactor? We never override `astReturns`, so it doesn‚Äôt need to be its own method; and it seems more organized to me if that logic is in `ast`, which we also never override.

I still wish we could move the `returns` field to be set as part of `astNode`, and maybe I‚Äôll make an attempt at trying to get that to work, but short of that I think this PR feels like an improvement in organization.

I also added some comments, please check that they‚Äôre correct. Is the returns thing because we need to wait for the children or the parents? Hopefully I got it right üòÑ

@helixbass I merged `master` into `ast` locally and ran the tests, and a bunch were failing related to numbers, which isn‚Äôt surprising since the recent changes on `master` involve support for `BigInt` and numeric separators. Basically, I think we need to revert two simplifications you made to the lexer's `numberToken` method:

1. We can‚Äôt use `Number.isFinite` to tell apart `Infinity` from other numbers. `BigInt`s are not finite, as they‚Äôre not numbers at all in JS; yet they‚Äôre still `NumericLiteral`s in our grammar.

2. We can‚Äôt use the `Number()` constructor to parse numbers, as it doesn‚Äôt support numeric separators (`Number('123_456')` returns `NaN`, not the `123456` we want/expect). The previous more complicated logic of detecting the base and using `parseInt` or `parseFloat` works, however, so I brought that back.

