I think there‚Äôs a fairly easy way to track our progress toward a ‚Äúcomplete‚Äù AST. So the [Babel AST spec](https://github.com/babel/babel/blob/master/packages/babylon/ast/spec.md) lists every one of Babel‚Äôs AST token types and properties. For example:

```js
interface RegExpLiteral <: Literal {
  type: "RegExpLiteral";
  pattern: string;
  flags: string;
}
```

Almost all of our node types have corresponding types in Babel‚Äôs AST spec. We could compare the AST output for our node against its counterpart in the Babel AST, and if both contain the same properties, that node type is complete. So for `RegExpLiteral`, if our node type has both the `pattern` and `flags` properties, and the values of those properties are roughly equivalent in terms of the information conveyed (if not necessarily the format or syntax) then our equivalent to Babel‚Äôs `RegExpLiteral` is done. Since Babel takes its AST as input to generate source code, by definition its AST is ‚Äúcomplete‚Äù in that it contains all the information needed for source code generation. If our AST contains the same information, it should be just as complete.

Comparing node types also has the advantage that we don‚Äôt need a code generation method (like Prettier) built yet. All we need is a ‚Äúkitchen sink‚Äù input file that has at least one of every node type, so it generates and AST that we can compare against Babel‚Äôs. @zdenko @helixbass

