This PR implements computed property keys (#4622) syntax for object literals.
```coffeescript
i = 0
a =
  ['foo' + ++i]: i
  ['foo' + ++i]: i
  ['foo' + ++i]: i

# a = {foo1: 1, foo2: 2, foo3: 3}

param = 'size'
config =
  [param]: 12,
  ['mobile' + param.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + param.slice(1)]: 4

# conf = {size: 12, mobileSize: 4}

obj =
  [Symbol.iterator]: ->
    yield "hello"
    yield "world"

# [obj...] = ['hello', 'world']
```

Besides basic support for ES spec, it also enables use of property value shorthand syntax.
```coffeescript
key = 'a'
obj = { [key] }
# obj = {a: 'a'}

key = 5
obj = { [key] }
# obj = {5: 5}

foo = (k) -> "key_#{k}"
obj = { [foo(1)] }
# obj = { key_1: 'key_1' }
```

This is similar to "object keys with interpolations". The only difference is that property values will be the same type as the key.
```coffeescript
obj = { [5] } => { 5: 5 }
obj = { ['5'] } => { '5': '5' }

obj = { "#{5}" } => { '5': '5' }
obj = { "#{'5'}" } => { '5': '5' }

```

I temporarily disabled few "unexpected object keys" test in `test/error_messages.coffee`  until I sort out some issues.

